{"title_page": "Nitish Kumar", "text_new": "{{for|the Canadian cricketer|Nitish Kumar (cricketer)}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2019}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Nitish Kumar \n| image = The Chief Minister of Bihar, Shri Nitish Kumar meeting with the Deputy Chairman, Planning Commission, Shri Montek Singh Ahluwalia to finalize Annual Plan 2007-08 of the State, in New Delhi on February 14, 2007 (Nitish Kumar) (cropped).jpg\n| nickname =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and  age|1951|3|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Bakhtiarpur]], [[Bihar]], [[India]]\n| alma_mater =  [[National Institute of Technology, Patna]] ([[Bachelor of Engineering|B.E.]]) \n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| constituency =\n| profession =  \n| party =[[Janata Dal (United)]]\n| spouse = Manju Kumari Sinha\n| children = 1\n| office1         = [[List of Chief Ministers of Bihar|22nd]] [[Chief Minister of Bihar]]\n| governor1= [[Keshari Nath Tripathi]]<br>[[Satya Pal Malik]]<br>[[Lalji Tandon]]<br>[[Phagu Chauhan]]\n| deputy1 = [[Sushil Kumar Modi]]\n| term_start1 = 27 July 2017\n| term_end1 =\n| predecessor1=\n|term_start2= 22 February 2015\n|term_end2=26 July 2017\n|predecessor2=[[Jitan Ram Manjhi]]\n|successor2=Himself\n| term_start3 = 24 November 2005\n| term_end3= 17 May 2014\n| predecessor3 = [[President's rule]]\n| successor3=[[Jitan Ram Manjhi]]\n| term_start4 = 3 March 2000\n| term_end4 = 10 March 2000\n| predecessor4 = [[Rabri Devi]]\n| successor4 = [[Rabri Devi]]\n| constituency4 =\n| office5 = [[Ministry of Railways (India)|Minister of Railways]]\n| term_start5 = 20 March 2001\n| term_end5 = 21 May 2004\n| predecessor5= [[Mamata Banerjee]]\n| successor5= [[Lalu Prasad Yadav]]\n| term_start6 = 19 March 1998\n| term_end6 = 5 August 1999\n| predecessor6= [[Ram Vilas Paswan]]\n| successor6 = [[Lalu Prasad Yadav]]\n| office7 = [[Ministry of Agriculture (India)|Minister of Agriculture]]\n| term_start7 = 27 May 2000\n| term_end7= 21 July 2001\n|primeminister7=[[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]]\n| predecessor7 =\n| successor7 =\n| term_start8 = 22 November 1999\n| term_end8= 3 March 2000\n|primeminister8=[[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]]\n| predecessor8 =\n| successor8 =\n| office9 = [[Ministry of Surface Transport (India)|Minister of Surface Transport]]\n| primeminister9 = [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]]\n| term_start9 = 13 October 1999\n| term_end9 = 22 November 1999\n| predecessor9=\n| successor9=\n| term_start10 = 14 April 1998\n| term_end10 = 5 August 1999\n|primeminister10=[[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]]\n| predecessor10 =\n| successor10 =\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Nitish Kumar''' (born 1 March 1951) is an Indian socialist politician and mass leader. He is the present [[Chief Minister (India)|Chief Minister]] of [[Bihar]], a state in India, since 2015 and has served in that role on five previous occasions.<ref>{{cite news|agency=PTI |url=https://www.firstpost.com/politics/nitish-kumar-sworn-in-as-cm-for-sixth-time-a-look-at-the-life-of-the-chanakya-of-bihar-politics-3861789.html |title=Nitish Kumar sworn-in as CM for sixth time: A look at the life of the 'Chanakya of Bihar politics' |work=Firstpost |date=27 July 2017 |accessdate=2019-01-02}}</ref> He has also served as a minister in the [[Government of India|Union Government of India]].\n\nKumar is a member of the [[Janata Dal (United)]] political party. He endeared himself to [[Biharis]], used to low expectations from previous regimes, when as Chief Minister, his socialist policies bore dividends in appointing more than 100,000 school teachers, ensuring that doctors worked in primary health centres, electrification of villages,<ref name=\"sify1\">{{cite news\n|url=http://sify.com/news/fullstory.php?a=jfbn4Ebeibj&title=Nitish_Kumar_s_development_agenda_makes_waves_in_Bihar&?vsv=TopHP3\n|title=Nitish Kumar's development agenda makes waves in Bihar\n|date=1 May 2009|work=Lok Sabha Elections 2009\n|publisher=Sify News\n|accessdate=26 May 2009}}</ref> paving of roads, cutting female illiteracy by half, turning around a lawless state by cracking down on criminals and doubling the income of the average Bihari.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Antholis|first1=William|title=New Players on the World Stage: Chinese Provinces and Indian States|url=http://www.brookings.edu/research/essays/2013/new-players-on-the-world-stage#section4|publisher=Brookings Institution|date=22 October 2013|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 May 2014, Kumar resigned, taking responsibility for his party's poor performance in the [[2014 Indian general election|2014 general elections]], and was succeeded by [[Jitan Ram Manjhi]]. However, he returned to office in February 2015 following a [[2015 Bihar political crisis|political crisis in Bihar]] and won the [[2015 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|state elections of November 2015]]. He was elected as the national president of his party on 10 April 2016. He resigned again on 26 July 2017 as Chief Minister of Bihar due to differences with the coalition partner, [[Rashtriya Janata Dal]] (RJD), following the naming of [[Tejashwi Yadav]], the Deputy Chief Minister and RJD member, in a [[First Information Report]] alleging corruption filed by the [[Central Bureau of Investigation]]. Hours later, he joined the [[National Democratic Alliance (India)|National Democratic Alliance]] (NDA) coalition, which had thus far been the opposition, and secured a majority in the assembly. He became Chief Minister again on the following day.\n\n==Early life==\nNitish Kumar was born on 1 March 1951 in [[Bakhtiarpur]], Bihar. His father, Kaviraj Ram Lakhan Singh, was an [[Ayurveda|ayurvedic practitioner]]; his mother was Parmeshwari Devi.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |url=http://gov.bih.nic.in/Governance/NitishKumar.htm |title=Chief Minister of Bihar |publisher=Government of Bihar |accessdate=2019-01-29}}</ref>\n\nKumar earned a degree in mechanical engineering from Bihar College of Engineering (now [[NIT Patna]]) in 1972.<ref name=\"ht20150818\"/> He joined the [[Bihar State Power Holding Company Limited|Bihar State Electricity Board]], half-heartedly, and later moved into politics.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-toi/special-report/I-dream-of-the-old-glory-days-of-Bihar/articleshow/11323112.cms | work=The Times Of India | title=I dream of the old glory days of Bihar |date=1 January 2012 |accessdate=21 October 2018}}</ref> He married Manju Kumari Sinha on 22 February 1973 and has one son.<ref name=\"bio\"/>\n\n==Political career==\nNitish Kumar belongs to a [[socialist]] class of politicians. During his early years as a politician he was associated with the likes of [[Jayaprakash Narayan]], [[Ram Manohar Lohia]], [[Satyendra Narayan Sinha|S. N. Sinha]], [[Karpuri Thakur]] and [[V. P. Singh]].<ref name=\"ht20150818\">{{cite news\n|url= http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/bihar-elections-the-leaders-who-matter-the-most/article1-1378907.aspx\n|title=Bihar leader-Mr. Nitish Kumar \n|work=Hindustan Times\n|date=18 August 2015\n|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://polityindia.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=192:a-politician-other-politicians-should-emulate-&catid=13:article&Itemid=61\n|title=A Politician other Politicians should Emulate!\n|publisher=Polityindia.com\n|date=18 January 2011\n|accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref> Kumar participated in Jayaprakash Narayan's movement between 1974 and 1977.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehinducentre.com/the-arena/current-issues/article25188707.ece|title= Jayaprakash Narayan- His Journey & Movements|website=www.thehinducentre.com|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref>.\n\n===Union Minister===\nKumar was briefly, the [[Ministry of Railways (India)|Union Minister for Railways]] and Minister for Surface Transport and later, the [[Ministry of Agriculture (India)|Minister for Agriculture]] in 1998\u201399, in the NDA government of [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]]. In August 1999, he resigned following the [[Gaisal train disaster]], for which he took responsibility as a minister. However, in his short stint as Railway Minister, he brought in widespread reforms, such as internet ticket booking facility in 2002,<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/2002/08/04/stories/2002080401231000.htm Railway online booking through credit cards]</ref><ref>[http://www.outlookindia.com/newswire/story/railway-reservation-through-internet/73655 Railway Reservation through internet]</ref> opening a record number of railway ticket booking counters and introducing the [[tatkal scheme]] for instant booking.\n\nLater that year, he rejoined the Union Cabinet as Minister for Agriculture. From 2001 to May 2004, he was \u2013 again \u2013 the Union Minister for Railways. In the 2004 Lok Sabha elections, he contested elections from two places, when he was elected from [[Nalanda]] but lost from his traditional constituency, [[Barh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/election/2004/may/13nitish.htm |title=Nitish Kumar voted out of Barh, wins in Nalanda |publisher=rediff.com |date=13 May 2004 |accessdate=23 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Chief Minister of Bihar===\n\nIn March 2000, Nitish was elected [[Chief Minister of Bihar]] for the first time at the behest of the Vajpayee Government in the center. NDA and allies had 151 MLA whereas Lalu Prasad Yadav had 159 MLA in 324 member house. Both alliances where lees then the majority mark that is 163. Nithish resigned before the could not prove his numbers in the house. <ref>[https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/march-2000-when-nitish-quit-as-cm-before-floor-test-779422.html March 2000: When Nitish quit as CM, before floor test]</ref><ref>[https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/nation/story/20000320-nitish-kumars-government-in-bihar-not-outvoted-as-much-as-outmanoeuvred-by-laloo-yadav-777236-2000-03-20 outvoted as much as outmanoeuvred by Laloo Yadav]</ref>\n\nKumar's government also initiated bicycle and meal programs. Giving bicycles to girls who stayed in school resulted in the state getting a huge number of girls into schools and a reduction in school dropout rates.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/asiaview/2010/11/indias_poorest_state&fsrc=nwl | work=The Economist | title=A triumph in Bihar | date=25 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Kumar's party swept back to power along with its then allies, the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], and he again became Chief Minister. The alliance won 206 seats, while the RJD won 22.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-25/india/28213318_1_nitish-kumar-bihar-hands-bihar-assembly-elections | work=The Times Of India | title=Nitish sweeps Bihar polls; Cong crushed, Lalu eclipsed | date=25 November 2010}}</ref> For the first time, electorates witnessed high turnout of women and young voters, while this was declared as the fairest election in Bihar, with no bloodshed or poll violence.<ref>on{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/a-landslide-sweep-for-jdubjp-combine-in-bihar/1/121031.html |title=A landslide sweep for JD(U)-BJP combine in Bihar : Election Updates, News - India Today |publisher=Indiatoday.intoday.in |date=24 November 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Resignation====\nOn 17 May 2014, Kumar submitted his resignation to the [[Governor of Bihar]], a day after his party fared poorly in the 2014 Lok Sabha elections, winning just 2 seats against 20 seats in the previous election. Kumar resigned, taking the moral responsibility of his party's poor performance in the election, and Jitan Ram Manjhi took over.<ref name=\"bp\">{{cite web|title=Nitish Kumar resigns as the Chief Minister of Bihar|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/05/nitish-kumar-resigns-as-the-chief-minister-of-bihar/|work=IANS|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n====2015 Bihar elections====\n\nKumar again became Chief Minister on 22 February 2015, on the backdrop of upcoming [[2015 Bihar Legislative Assembly election]], considered to be his toughest election to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scroll.in/article/745887/frenemies-nitish-kumar-and-lalu-yadav-finally-reach-breakthrough-in-seat-sharing-talks|title=Frenemies Nitish Kumar and Lalu Yadav finally reach breakthrough in seat-sharing talks}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.in/nitish-kumar-/bihar-elections-2015-impa_b_7917778.html|title=Why The Upcoming Election In Bihar Is Critical For The State And Beyond}}</ref> His JD(U), along with RJD and Congress, formed the Mahagathbandhan (Grand Alliance) to counter the BJP in Bihar.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.abplive.in/india/2015/02/22/article508925.ece/My-priority-is-to-work-for-Bihars-development-Nitish-Kumar| work=ABP News| title=Nitish Kumar returns as Bihar CM| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223084835/http://www.abplive.in/india/2015/02/22/article508925.ece/My-priority-is-to-work-for-Bihars-development-Nitish-Kumar| archivedate=23 February 2015| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nKumar campaigned aggressively during the elections for the Grand Alliance, countering the allegations raised by Narendra Modi and the BJP.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sajjad|first1=Mohammad|title=How Nitish Kumar and Lalu Yadav won Bihar|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/column/how-nitish-kumar-and-lalu-yadav-won-bihar/20151108.htm|accessdate=9 November 2015|publisher=rediff.com|date=8 November 2015}}</ref> The Grand Alliance won the Assembly election by a margin of 178 over the BJP and its allies, with RJD emerging as the largest party with 80 seats and JD(U) placed second with 71.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/nitish-kumar-wont-contest-polls-will-devote-time-for-campaigning-rabri-devi/1/455939.html|title=Won't contest Bihar polls, will devote time for campaigning, says Nitish Kumar}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/wont-contest-bihar-elections-nitish-kumar/articleshow/48329857.cms|title=Won't contest Bihar elections: Nitish Kumar}}</ref> Kumar was sworn in as Chief Minister on 20 November 2015 for a record fifth time and Tejashwi Yadav became [[Deputy Chief Minister of Bihar]].\n\nKumar's campaign was managed by the Indian Political Action Committee (I-PAC) who were hired to managed the campaign for JD(U).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news18.com/news/politics/how-ipac-made-it-click-for-nitish-kumar-in-bihar-1162279.html|title=How IPAC made it click for Nitish Kumar in Bihar|work=News18|access-date=2018-09-29}}</ref> I-PAC designed the campaign strategy which included reaching out to a larger set of voters through innovative campaigns, including sending hundreds of branded cycles for outreach,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thequint.com/news/politics/how-prashant-kishors-team-swung-the-elections-for-nitish-kumar|title=How Prashant Kishor\u2019s Team Swung the Elections for Nitish Kumar|work=The Quint|access-date=2018-09-29|language=en}}</ref> Har Ghar Dastak (door-to-door outreach)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/sunday-story-the-leader-and-his-machine/|title=Sunday Story: The Leader and his machine|date=5 July 2015|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-09-29|language=en-US}}</ref> and the DNA campaign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/prashant-kishor-man-behind-modi-ls-campaign-crafts-nitish-win/story-fgqyNqnz6MSVwerb86OHdJ.html|title=Prashant Kishor: Man behind Modi LS campaign crafts Nitish win|date=8 November 2015|work=Hindustan Times|access-date=2018-09-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Mahagathbandhan breakup====\n\nWhen corruption charges were leveled against Tejashwi Yadav, the Deputy Chief Minister, Kumar asked for him to resign from the cabinet. The RJD refused to countenance this and so, in order to protect his clean image and zero tolerance towards corruption, Kumar resigned on 26 July 2017, thus ending the Grand Alliance. He joined the principal opposition, the NDA, and came back to power within a few hours.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/nitish-kumar-resigns-as-bihar-chief-minister-tejashwi-yadav-lalu-yadav-grand-alliance-jdu-meeting-governor-4768045/|title=Nitish Kumar resigns as Bihar Chief Minister, says had become 'difficult for me to work'|date=26 July 2017|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2017-07-26}}</ref>\n\n==Biographies==\n*[[Sankarshan Thakur]] authored a book based on his life titled ''Single Man: The Life and Times of Nitish Kumar of Bihar''.<ref>[http://www.rediff.com/news/slide-show/slide-show-1-when-nitish-cancelled-the-modi-dinner/20140228.htm When Nitish Kumar cancelled the Modi dinner]</ref>\n*Arun Sinha has authored a book titled ''Nitish Kumar and The Rise of Bihar''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/books/the-man-who-transformed-bihar/article3013622.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | first=T. | last=Ramakrishnan | title=The man who transformed Bihar | date=19 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\n\n* Anuvrat Puraskar, by Shwetambar Terapanthi Mahasabha (Jain organisation), for enforcing total prohibition on liquor in Bihar, 2017\n* JP Memorial Award, Nagpur's Manav Mandir, 2013<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/The-day-Patil-took-oath-of-office-on-Friday-he-honoured-Nitish-with-the-JP-Memorial-Award-on-behalf-of-Nagpurs-Manav-Mandir-/articleshow/19150828.cms |title=The day Patil took oath of office on Friday he honoured Nitish with the JP Memorial Award on behalf of Nagpur's Manav Mandir. |work=The Times of India |date=23 March 2013 |accessdate=2018-10-21}}</ref>\n* Ranked 77th in ''[[Foreign Policy Magazine]]''{{'}} top 100 global thinkers 2012<ref>{{cite news|title=Nitish Kumar in Foreign Policy's top 100 global thinkers|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/nitish-kumar-foreign-policy-top-100-global-thinkers/1/234869.html|accessdate=14 June 2016|publisher=indiatoday.intoday.in}}</ref>\n* [[XLRI]], Jamshedpur Sir Jehangir Ghandy Medal for Industrial & Social Peace 2011<ref>{{cite web|author=Our Bureau |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/industry-and-economy/economy/article1571232.ece |title=Business Line : Industry & Economy / Economy : XLRI to fete Nitish Kumar |publisher=Thehindubusinessline.com |date= |accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref>\n* \"MSN Indian of the Year 2010\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.in.msn.com/national/article.aspx?cp-documentid=4719413 |title=MSN Indian Of The Year: Nitish Kumar |publisher=News.in.msn.com |date=20 December 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615165648/http://news.in.msn.com/national/article.aspx?cp-documentid=4719413 |archive-date=15 June 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[NDTV Indian of the Year]] \u2013 Politics, 2010<ref>{{cite web|author=NDTV Indian of the Year: The winners |url=http://www.ndtv.com/video/shows/indian-of-the-year/ndtv-s-indian-of-the-year-awards-2010-191081 |title=NDTV Indian of the Year: The winners |publisher=NDTV.com |date=18 February 2011 |accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref>\n* ''[[Forbes]]''{{'}} \"India's Person of the Year\", 2010<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/2011/01/03/forbes-india-person-of-the-year-nitish-kumar.html | work=Forbes | title=A Person of the Year: Nitish Kumar | date=3 January 2011}}</ref>\n* [[CNN-IBN]] \"Indian of the Year Award\" \u2013 Politics, 2010<ref>[http://ibnlive.in.com/videos/137243/cnnibn-ioty-in-politics-nitish-kumar.html Nitish Kumar, CNN IBN Indian of the year-2010]</ref>\n* NDTV Indian of the Year \u2013 Politics, 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/news/videos/video_player.php?id=1204670 |title=News \" Videos |publisher=NDTV |date= |accessdate=2012-09-17}}</ref>\n* ''Economics Times'' \"Business Reformer of the Year 2009\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/articleshow/4931000.cms |work=The Times Of India |location=India | title=Features | date=25 August 2009}}</ref>\n* Polio Eradication Championship Award 2009, by Rotary International<ref>{{cite news| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/Awards-galore-for-Nitish/articleshow/7153302.cms |work=The Times Of India |location=India | title=Awards galore for Nitish |date=24 December 2010}}</ref>\n* [[CNN-IBN]] Great Indian of the Year \u2013 Politics, 2008<ref>[http://www.indianoftheyear.com/index08.php Indian Of The Year 2008 -politics winner nitish kumar] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713025026/http://www.indianoftheyear.com/index08.php |date=13 July 2011 }}</ref>\n* The Best [[Chief Minister]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/features/rday/stateofthenation/cm.php |title=IBN |publisher=Ibnlive.in.com |accessdate=2012-09-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120424025902/http://ibnlive.in.com/features/rday/stateofthenation/cm.php |archivedate=24 April 2012 }}</ref> according to the [[CNN-IBN]] and ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' State of the Nation Poll 2007\n\n==Positions held==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Period\n! Positions\n! Note\n|-\n|1977\n|Contested first assembly elections on a [[Janata Party]] ticket\n|\n|-\n|1985\u201389\n|Member, Bihar Legislative Assembly\n|First term in Legislative Assembly\n|-\n|1986\u201387\n|Member, Committee on Petitions, Bihar Legislative Assembly\n|\n|-\n|1987\u201388\n|President, Yuva Lok Dal, Bihar\n|\n|-\n|1987\u201389\n|Member, Committee on Public Undertakings, Bihar Legislative Assembly.\n|\n|-\n|1989\n|Secretary-General, [[Janata Dal]], Bihar\n|\n|-\n|1989\n|Elected to [[9th Lok Sabha]].\n|First term in [[Lok Sabha]]\n|-\n|1989 - 16 July 1990\n|Member, House Committee\n|Resigned\n|-\n|April 1990\u2013November 1990\n|Union Minister of State, Agriculture and Co-operation\n|\n|-\n|1991\n|Re-elected to [[10th Lok Sabha]]\n|2nd term in Lok Sabha\n|-\n|1991\u201393\n|General-Secretary, Janata Dal. <br/>Deputy Leader of Janata Dal in Parliament\n|\n|-\n|17 December 1991 \u2013 10 May 1996\n|Member, Railway Convention Committee\n|\n|-\n|8 April 1993 \u2013 10 May 1996\n|Chairman, Committee on Agriculture\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|Re-elected to [[11th Lok Sabha]]. <br/> Member, Committee on Estimates. <br/>Member, General Purposes Committee.<br/> Member, Joint Committee on the Constitution (Eighty-first Amendment Bill, 1996)\n|Third term in Lok Sabha\n|-\n|1996\u201398\n|Member, Committee on Defence\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|Re-elected to [[12th Lok Sabha]]\n|4th term in Lok Sabha\n|-\n|19 March 1998 \u2013 5 August 1999\n|Union Cabinet Minister, Railways\n|\n|-\n|14 April 1998 \u2013 5 August 1999\n|Union Cabinet Minister, Surface Transport (additional charge)\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|Re-elected to [[13th Lok Sabha]]\n|5th term in Lok Sabha\n|-\n|13 October 1999 \u2013 22 November 1999\n|Union Cabinet Minister, Surface Transport\n|\n|-\n|22 November 1999 \u2013 3 March 2000\n|Union Cabinet Minister, Agriculture\n|\n|-\n|3 March 2000 \u2013 10 March 2000\n|Chief Minister, Bihar\n| as 29th Chief Minister of Bihar, only for 7 days\n|-\n|27 May 2000 \u2013 20 March 2001\n|Union Cabinet Minister, Agriculture\n|\n|-\n|20 March 2001 \u2013 21 July 2001\n|Union Cabinet Minister, Agriculture, with additional charge of Railways\n|\n|-\n|22 July 2001 \u2013 21 May 2004\n|Union Cabinet Minister, Railways\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|Re-elected to [[14th Lok Sabha]]. <br/>Member, Committee on Coal & Steel. <br/>Member, General Purposes Committee. <br/>Member, Committee of Privileges. <br/>Leader Janata Dal (U) Parliamentary Party, Lok Sabha\n|6th term in Lok Sabha\n|-\n|24 November 2005 \u2013 24 November 2010\n|Chief Minister, Bihar\n| as 31st Chief Minister of Bihar\n|-\n|26 November 2010 \u2013 17 May 2014\n|Chief Minister, Bihar\n| as 32nd Chief Minister of Bihar\n|-\n|22 February 2015 \u2013 19 November 2015\n|Chief Minister, Bihar\n| as 34th Chief Minister of Bihar\n|-\n|20 November 2015 \u2013 26 July 2017\n|Chief Minister, Bihar\n|as 35th Chief Minister of Bihar<br />\n|-\n|27 July 2017 -\n|Chief Minister,Bihar\n|as 36th Chief Minister of Bihar\n|}\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://nitishspeaks.blogspot.in/ Official Blog]\n* [http://gov.bih.nic.in/Governance/NitishKumar.htm Biography on Bihar Government website]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box\n||before=[[President's rule]]\n|title=[[Chief Minister of Bihar]]\n|years=24 November 2005{{spaced ndash}}17 May 2014\n|after=[[Jitan Ram Manjhi]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n||before=[[Jitan Ram Manjhi]]\n|title=[[Chief Minister of Bihar]]\n|years=22 February 2015{{spaced ndash}}\n|after=''incumbent''\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Chief Ministers of Bihar}}\n{{Current Indian Chief Ministers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kumar, Nitish}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Nalanda]]\n[[Category:14th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:Chief Ministers of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Janata Dal politicians]]\n[[Category:Janata Dal (United) politicians]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Bihar]]\n[[Category:Railway Ministers of India]]\n[[Category:Agriculture Ministers of India]]\n[[Category:V. P. Singh administration]]\n[[Category:9th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:10th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:11th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:12th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:13th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bihar Legislative Council]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Canadian cricketer|Nitish Kumar (cricketer)}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2019}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Nitish Kumar \n| image = The Chief Minister of Bihar, Shri Nitish Kumar meeting with the Deputy Chairman, Planning Commission, Shri Montek Singh Ahluwalia to finalize Annual Plan 2007-08 of the State, in New Delhi on February 14, 2007 (Nitish Kumar) (cropped).jpg\n| nickname =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and  age|1951|3|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Bakhtiarpur]], [[Bihar]], [[India]]\n| alma_mater =  [[National Institute of Technology, Patna]] ([[Bachelor of Engineering|B.E.]]) \n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| constituency =\n| profession =  \n| party =[[Janata Dal (United)]]\n| spouse = Manju Kumari Sinha\n| children = 1\n| office1         = [[List of Chief Ministers of Bihar|22nd]] [[Chief Minister of Bihar]]\n| governor1= [[Keshari Nath Tripathi]]<br>[[Satya Pal Malik]]<br>[[Lalji Tandon]]<br>[[Phagu Chauhan]]\n| deputy1 = [[Sushil Kumar Modi]]\n| term_start1 = 27 July 2017\n| term_end1 =\n| predecessor1=\n|term_start2= 22 February 2015\n|term_end2=26 July 2017\n|predecessor2=[[Jitan Ram Manjhi]]\n|successor2=Himself\n| term_start3 = 24 November 2005\n| term_end3= 17 May 2014\n| predecessor3 = [[President's rule]]\n| successor3=[[Jitan Ram Manjhi]]\n| term_start4 = 3 March 2000\n| term_end4 = 10 March 2000\n| predecessor4 = [[Rabri Devi]]\n| successor4 = [[Rabri Devi]]\n| constituency4 =\n| office5 = [[Ministry of Railways (India)|Minister of Railways]]\n| term_start5 = 20 March 2001\n| term_end5 = 21 May 2004\n| predecessor5= [[Mamata Banerjee]]\n| successor5= [[Lalu Prasad Yadav]]\n| term_start6 = 19 March 1998\n| term_end6 = 5 August 1999\n| predecessor6= [[Ram Vilas Paswan]]\n| successor6 = [[Lalu Prasad Yadav]]\n| office7 = [[Ministry of Agriculture (India)|Minister of Agriculture]]\n| term_start7 = 27 May 2000\n| term_end7= 21 July 2001\n|primeminister7=[[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]]\n| predecessor7 =\n| successor7 =\n| term_start8 = 22 November 1999\n| term_end8= 3 March 2000\n|primeminister8=[[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]]\n| predecessor8 =\n| successor8 =\n| office9 = [[Ministry of Surface Transport (India)|Minister of Surface Transport]]\n| primeminister9 = [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]]\n| term_start9 = 13 October 1999\n| term_end9 = 22 November 1999\n| predecessor9=\n| successor9=\n| term_start10 = 14 April 1998\n| term_end10 = 5 August 1999\n|primeminister10=[[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]]\n| predecessor10 =\n| successor10 =\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Nitish Kumar''' (born 1 March 1951) is an Indian politician. He is the present [[Chief Minister (India)|Chief Minister]] of [[Bihar]], a state in India, since 2015 and has served in that role on five previous occasions.<ref>{{cite news|agency=PTI |url=https://www.firstpost.com/politics/nitish-kumar-sworn-in-as-cm-for-sixth-time-a-look-at-the-life-of-the-chanakya-of-bihar-politics-3861789.html |title=Nitish Kumar sworn-in as CM for sixth time: A look at the life of the 'Chanakya of Bihar politics' |work=Firstpost |date=27 July 2017 |accessdate=2019-01-02}}</ref> He has also served as a minister in the [[Government of India|Union Government of India]].\n\nKumar is a member of the [[Janata Dal (United)]] political party. He endeared himself to [[Biharis]], used to low expectations from previous regimes, when as Chief Minister, his socialist policies bore dividends in appointing more than 100,000 school teachers, ensuring that doctors worked in primary health centres, electrification of villages,<ref name=\"sify1\">{{cite news\n|url=http://sify.com/news/fullstory.php?a=jfbn4Ebeibj&title=Nitish_Kumar_s_development_agenda_makes_waves_in_Bihar&?vsv=TopHP3\n|title=Nitish Kumar's development agenda makes waves in Bihar\n|date=1 May 2009|work=Lok Sabha Elections 2009\n|publisher=Sify News\n|accessdate=26 May 2009}}</ref> paving of roads, cutting female illiteracy by half, turning around a lawless state by cracking down on criminals and doubling the income of the average Bihari.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Antholis|first1=William|title=New Players on the World Stage: Chinese Provinces and Indian States|url=http://www.brookings.edu/research/essays/2013/new-players-on-the-world-stage#section4|publisher=Brookings Institution|date=22 October 2013|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 May 2014, Kumar resigned, taking responsibility for his party's poor performance in the [[2014 Indian general election|2014 general elections]], and was succeeded by [[Jitan Ram Manjhi]]. However, he returned to office in February 2015 following a [[2015 Bihar political crisis|political crisis in Bihar]] and won the [[2015 Bihar Legislative Assembly election|state elections of November 2015]]. He was elected as the national president of his party on 10 April 2016. He resigned again on 26 July 2017 as Chief Minister of Bihar due to differences with the coalition partner, [[Rashtriya Janata Dal]] (RJD), following the naming of [[Tejashwi Yadav]], the Deputy Chief Minister and RJD member, in a [[First Information Report]] alleging corruption filed by the [[Central Bureau of Investigation]]. Hours later, he joined the [[National Democratic Alliance (India)|National Democratic Alliance]] (NDA) coalition, which had thus far been the opposition, and secured a majority in the assembly. He became Chief Minister again on the following day.\n\n==Early life==\nNitish Kumar was born on 1 March 1951 in [[Bakhtiarpur]], Bihar. His father, Kaviraj Ram Lakhan Singh, was an [[Ayurveda|ayurvedic practitioner]]; his mother was Parmeshwari Devi.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |url=http://gov.bih.nic.in/Governance/NitishKumar.htm |title=Chief Minister of Bihar |publisher=Government of Bihar |accessdate=2019-01-29}}</ref>\n\nKumar earned a degree in mechanical engineering from Bihar College of Engineering (now [[NIT Patna]]) in 1972.<ref name=\"ht20150818\"/> He joined the [[Bihar State Power Holding Company Limited|Bihar State Electricity Board]], half-heartedly, and later moved into politics.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-toi/special-report/I-dream-of-the-old-glory-days-of-Bihar/articleshow/11323112.cms | work=The Times Of India | title=I dream of the old glory days of Bihar |date=1 January 2012 |accessdate=21 October 2018}}</ref> He married Manju Kumari Sinha on 22 February 1973 and has one son.<ref name=\"bio\"/>\n\n==Political career==\nNitish Kumar belongs to a [[socialist]] class of politicians. During his early years as a politician he was associated with the likes of [[Jayaprakash Narayan]], [[Ram Manohar Lohia]], [[Satyendra Narayan Sinha|S. N. Sinha]], [[Karpuri Thakur]] and [[V. P. Singh]].<ref name=\"ht20150818\">{{cite news\n|url= http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/bihar-elections-the-leaders-who-matter-the-most/article1-1378907.aspx\n|title=Bihar leader-Mr. Nitish Kumar \n|work=Hindustan Times\n|date=18 August 2015\n|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://polityindia.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=192:a-politician-other-politicians-should-emulate-&catid=13:article&Itemid=61\n|title=A Politician other Politicians should Emulate!\n|publisher=Polityindia.com\n|date=18 January 2011\n|accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref> Kumar participated in Jayaprakash Narayan's movement between 1974 and 1977.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehinducentre.com/the-arena/current-issues/article25188707.ece|title= Jayaprakash Narayan- His Journey & Movements|website=www.thehinducentre.com|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref>.\n\n===Union Minister===\nKumar was briefly, the [[Ministry of Railways (India)|Union Minister for Railways]] and Minister for Surface Transport and later, the [[Ministry of Agriculture (India)|Minister for Agriculture]] in 1998\u201399, in the NDA government of [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]]. In August 1999, he resigned following the [[Gaisal train disaster]], for which he took responsibility as a minister. However, in his short stint as Railway Minister, he brought in widespread reforms, such as internet ticket booking facility in 2002,<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/2002/08/04/stories/2002080401231000.htm Railway online booking through credit cards]</ref><ref>[http://www.outlookindia.com/newswire/story/railway-reservation-through-internet/73655 Railway Reservation through internet]</ref> opening a record number of railway ticket booking counters and introducing the [[tatkal scheme]] for instant booking.\n\nLater that year, he rejoined the Union Cabinet as Minister for Agriculture. From 2001 to May 2004, he was \u2013 again \u2013 the Union Minister for Railways. In the 2004 Lok Sabha elections, he contested elections from two places, when he was elected from [[Nalanda]] but lost from his traditional constituency, [[Barh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/election/2004/may/13nitish.htm |title=Nitish Kumar voted out of Barh, wins in Nalanda |publisher=rediff.com |date=13 May 2004 |accessdate=23 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Chief Minister of Bihar===\n\nIn March 2000, Nitish was elected [[Chief Minister of Bihar]] for the first time at the behest of the Vajpayee Government in the center. NDA and allies had 151 MLA whereas Lalu Prasad Yadav had 159 MLA in 324 member house. Both alliances where lees then the majority mark that is 163. Nithish resigned before the could not prove his numbers in the house. <ref>[https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/march-2000-when-nitish-quit-as-cm-before-floor-test-779422.html March 2000: When Nitish quit as CM, before floor test]</ref><ref>[https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/nation/story/20000320-nitish-kumars-government-in-bihar-not-outvoted-as-much-as-outmanoeuvred-by-laloo-yadav-777236-2000-03-20 outvoted as much as outmanoeuvred by Laloo Yadav]</ref>\n\nKumar's government also initiated bicycle and meal programs. Giving bicycles to girls who stayed in school resulted in the state getting a huge number of girls into schools and a reduction in school dropout rates.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/asiaview/2010/11/indias_poorest_state&fsrc=nwl | work=The Economist | title=A triumph in Bihar | date=25 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Kumar's party swept back to power along with its then allies, the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], and he again became Chief Minister. The alliance won 206 seats, while the RJD won 22.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-25/india/28213318_1_nitish-kumar-bihar-hands-bihar-assembly-elections | work=The Times Of India | title=Nitish sweeps Bihar polls; Cong crushed, Lalu eclipsed | date=25 November 2010}}</ref> For the first time, electorates witnessed high turnout of women and young voters, while this was declared as the fairest election in Bihar, with no bloodshed or poll violence.<ref>on{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/a-landslide-sweep-for-jdubjp-combine-in-bihar/1/121031.html |title=A landslide sweep for JD(U)-BJP combine in Bihar : Election Updates, News - India Today |publisher=Indiatoday.intoday.in |date=24 November 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Resignation====\nOn 17 May 2014, Kumar submitted his resignation to the [[Governor of Bihar]], a day after his party fared poorly in the 2014 Lok Sabha elections, winning just 2 seats against 20 seats in the previous election. Kumar resigned, taking the moral responsibility of his party's poor performance in the election, and Jitan Ram Manjhi took over.<ref name=\"bp\">{{cite web|title=Nitish Kumar resigns as the Chief Minister of Bihar|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/05/nitish-kumar-resigns-as-the-chief-minister-of-bihar/|work=IANS|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n====2015 Bihar elections====\n\nKumar again became Chief Minister on 22 February 2015, on the backdrop of upcoming [[2015 Bihar Legislative Assembly election]], considered to be his toughest election to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scroll.in/article/745887/frenemies-nitish-kumar-and-lalu-yadav-finally-reach-breakthrough-in-seat-sharing-talks|title=Frenemies Nitish Kumar and Lalu Yadav finally reach breakthrough in seat-sharing talks}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.in/nitish-kumar-/bihar-elections-2015-impa_b_7917778.html|title=Why The Upcoming Election In Bihar Is Critical For The State And Beyond}}</ref> His JD(U), along with RJD and Congress, formed the Mahagathbandhan (Grand Alliance) to counter the BJP in Bihar.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.abplive.in/india/2015/02/22/article508925.ece/My-priority-is-to-work-for-Bihars-development-Nitish-Kumar| work=ABP News| title=Nitish Kumar returns as Bihar CM| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223084835/http://www.abplive.in/india/2015/02/22/article508925.ece/My-priority-is-to-work-for-Bihars-development-Nitish-Kumar| archivedate=23 February 2015| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nKumar campaigned aggressively during the elections for the Grand Alliance, countering the allegations raised by Narendra Modi and the BJP.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sajjad|first1=Mohammad|title=How Nitish Kumar and Lalu Yadav won Bihar|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/column/how-nitish-kumar-and-lalu-yadav-won-bihar/20151108.htm|accessdate=9 November 2015|publisher=rediff.com|date=8 November 2015}}</ref> The Grand Alliance won the Assembly election by a margin of 178 over the BJP and its allies, with RJD emerging as the largest party with 80 seats and JD(U) placed second with 71.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/nitish-kumar-wont-contest-polls-will-devote-time-for-campaigning-rabri-devi/1/455939.html|title=Won't contest Bihar polls, will devote time for campaigning, says Nitish Kumar}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/wont-contest-bihar-elections-nitish-kumar/articleshow/48329857.cms|title=Won't contest Bihar elections: Nitish Kumar}}</ref> Kumar was sworn in as Chief Minister on 20 November 2015 for a record fifth time and Tejashwi Yadav became [[Deputy Chief Minister of Bihar]].\n\nKumar's campaign was managed by the Indian Political Action Committee (I-PAC) who were hired to managed the campaign for JD(U).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news18.com/news/politics/how-ipac-made-it-click-for-nitish-kumar-in-bihar-1162279.html|title=How IPAC made it click for Nitish Kumar in Bihar|work=News18|access-date=2018-09-29}}</ref> I-PAC designed the campaign strategy which included reaching out to a larger set of voters through innovative campaigns, including sending hundreds of branded cycles for outreach,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thequint.com/news/politics/how-prashant-kishors-team-swung-the-elections-for-nitish-kumar|title=How Prashant Kishor\u2019s Team Swung the Elections for Nitish Kumar|work=The Quint|access-date=2018-09-29|language=en}}</ref> Har Ghar Dastak (door-to-door outreach)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/sunday-story-the-leader-and-his-machine/|title=Sunday Story: The Leader and his machine|date=5 July 2015|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-09-29|language=en-US}}</ref> and the DNA campaign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/prashant-kishor-man-behind-modi-ls-campaign-crafts-nitish-win/story-fgqyNqnz6MSVwerb86OHdJ.html|title=Prashant Kishor: Man behind Modi LS campaign crafts Nitish win|date=8 November 2015|work=Hindustan Times|access-date=2018-09-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Mahagathbandhan breakup====\n\nWhen corruption charges were leveled against Tejashwi Yadav, the Deputy Chief Minister, Kumar asked for him to resign from the cabinet. The RJD refused to countenance this and so, in order to protect his clean image and zero tolerance towards corruption, Kumar resigned on 26 July 2017, thus ending the Grand Alliance. He joined the principal opposition, the NDA, and came back to power within a few hours.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/nitish-kumar-resigns-as-bihar-chief-minister-tejashwi-yadav-lalu-yadav-grand-alliance-jdu-meeting-governor-4768045/|title=Nitish Kumar resigns as Bihar Chief Minister, says had become 'difficult for me to work'|date=26 July 2017|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2017-07-26}}</ref>\n\n==Biographies==\n*[[Sankarshan Thakur]] authored a book based on his life titled ''Single Man: The Life and Times of Nitish Kumar of Bihar''.<ref>[http://www.rediff.com/news/slide-show/slide-show-1-when-nitish-cancelled-the-modi-dinner/20140228.htm When Nitish Kumar cancelled the Modi dinner]</ref>\n*Arun Sinha has authored a book titled ''Nitish Kumar and The Rise of Bihar''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/books/the-man-who-transformed-bihar/article3013622.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | first=T. | last=Ramakrishnan | title=The man who transformed Bihar | date=19 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\n\n* Anuvrat Puraskar, by Shwetambar Terapanthi Mahasabha (Jain organisation), for enforcing total prohibition on liquor in Bihar, 2017\n* JP Memorial Award, Nagpur's Manav Mandir, 2013<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/The-day-Patil-took-oath-of-office-on-Friday-he-honoured-Nitish-with-the-JP-Memorial-Award-on-behalf-of-Nagpurs-Manav-Mandir-/articleshow/19150828.cms |title=The day Patil took oath of office on Friday he honoured Nitish with the JP Memorial Award on behalf of Nagpur's Manav Mandir. |work=The Times of India |date=23 March 2013 |accessdate=2018-10-21}}</ref>\n* Ranked 77th in ''[[Foreign Policy Magazine]]''{{'}} top 100 global thinkers 2012<ref>{{cite news|title=Nitish Kumar in Foreign Policy's top 100 global thinkers|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/nitish-kumar-foreign-policy-top-100-global-thinkers/1/234869.html|accessdate=14 June 2016|publisher=indiatoday.intoday.in}}</ref>\n* [[XLRI]], Jamshedpur Sir Jehangir Ghandy Medal for Industrial & Social Peace 2011<ref>{{cite web|author=Our Bureau |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/industry-and-economy/economy/article1571232.ece |title=Business Line : Industry & Economy / Economy : XLRI to fete Nitish Kumar |publisher=Thehindubusinessline.com |date= |accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref>\n* \"MSN Indian of the Year 2010\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.in.msn.com/national/article.aspx?cp-documentid=4719413 |title=MSN Indian Of The Year: Nitish Kumar |publisher=News.in.msn.com |date=20 December 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615165648/http://news.in.msn.com/national/article.aspx?cp-documentid=4719413 |archive-date=15 June 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[NDTV Indian of the Year]] \u2013 Politics, 2010<ref>{{cite web|author=NDTV Indian of the Year: The winners |url=http://www.ndtv.com/video/shows/indian-of-the-year/ndtv-s-indian-of-the-year-awards-2010-191081 |title=NDTV Indian of the Year: The winners |publisher=NDTV.com |date=18 February 2011 |accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref>\n* ''[[Forbes]]''{{'}} \"India's Person of the Year\", 2010<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/2011/01/03/forbes-india-person-of-the-year-nitish-kumar.html | work=Forbes | title=A Person of the Year: Nitish Kumar | date=3 January 2011}}</ref>\n* [[CNN-IBN]] \"Indian of the Year Award\" \u2013 Politics, 2010<ref>[http://ibnlive.in.com/videos/137243/cnnibn-ioty-in-politics-nitish-kumar.html Nitish Kumar, CNN IBN Indian of the year-2010]</ref>\n* NDTV Indian of the Year \u2013 Politics, 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/news/videos/video_player.php?id=1204670 |title=News \" Videos |publisher=NDTV |date= |accessdate=2012-09-17}}</ref>\n* ''Economics Times'' \"Business Reformer of the Year 2009\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/articleshow/4931000.cms |work=The Times Of India |location=India | title=Features | date=25 August 2009}}</ref>\n* Polio Eradication Championship Award 2009, by Rotary International<ref>{{cite news| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/Awards-galore-for-Nitish/articleshow/7153302.cms |work=The Times Of India |location=India | title=Awards galore for Nitish |date=24 December 2010}}</ref>\n* [[CNN-IBN]] Great Indian of the Year \u2013 Politics, 2008<ref>[http://www.indianoftheyear.com/index08.php Indian Of The Year 2008 -politics winner nitish kumar] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713025026/http://www.indianoftheyear.com/index08.php |date=13 July 2011 }}</ref>\n* The Best [[Chief Minister]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/features/rday/stateofthenation/cm.php |title=IBN |publisher=Ibnlive.in.com |accessdate=2012-09-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120424025902/http://ibnlive.in.com/features/rday/stateofthenation/cm.php |archivedate=24 April 2012 }}</ref> according to the [[CNN-IBN]] and ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' State of the Nation Poll 2007\n\n==Positions held==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Period\n! Positions\n! Note\n|-\n|1977\n|Contested first assembly elections on a [[Janata Party]] ticket\n|\n|-\n|1985\u201389\n|Member, Bihar Legislative Assembly\n|First term in Legislative Assembly\n|-\n|1986\u201387\n|Member, Committee on Petitions, Bihar Legislative Assembly\n|\n|-\n|1987\u201388\n|President, Yuva Lok Dal, Bihar\n|\n|-\n|1987\u201389\n|Member, Committee on Public Undertakings, Bihar Legislative Assembly.\n|\n|-\n|1989\n|Secretary-General, [[Janata Dal]], Bihar\n|\n|-\n|1989\n|Elected to [[9th Lok Sabha]].\n|First term in [[Lok Sabha]]\n|-\n|1989 - 16 July 1990\n|Member, House Committee\n|Resigned\n|-\n|April 1990\u2013November 1990\n|Union Minister of State, Agriculture and Co-operation\n|\n|-\n|1991\n|Re-elected to [[10th Lok Sabha]]\n|2nd term in Lok Sabha\n|-\n|1991\u201393\n|General-Secretary, Janata Dal. <br/>Deputy Leader of Janata Dal in Parliament\n|\n|-\n|17 December 1991 \u2013 10 May 1996\n|Member, Railway Convention Committee\n|\n|-\n|8 April 1993 \u2013 10 May 1996\n|Chairman, Committee on Agriculture\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|Re-elected to [[11th Lok Sabha]]. <br/> Member, Committee on Estimates. <br/>Member, General Purposes Committee.<br/> Member, Joint Committee on the Constitution (Eighty-first Amendment Bill, 1996)\n|Third term in Lok Sabha\n|-\n|1996\u201398\n|Member, Committee on Defence\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|Re-elected to [[12th Lok Sabha]]\n|4th term in Lok Sabha\n|-\n|19 March 1998 \u2013 5 August 1999\n|Union Cabinet Minister, Railways\n|\n|-\n|14 April 1998 \u2013 5 August 1999\n|Union Cabinet Minister, Surface Transport (additional charge