{"title_page": "Sarah D. Goode", "text_new": "<noinclude><!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Sarah D. Goode|timestamp=20200410170421|year=2020|month=April|day=10|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Sarah D. Goode|date=10 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point --></noinclude>\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix   = Dr\n| name               = Sarah D. Goode\n| honorific_suffix   = PhD\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         = <!-- use only if different from full/othernames -->\n| birth_date         = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}}  -->\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| region             = \n| nationality        = British\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = CEO, writer\n| period             = \n| known_for          = {{Plainlist|\n* ''[[Understanding and Addressing Adult Sexual Attraction to Children]]''\n* ''Paedophiles in Society''}}\n| title              = \n| boards             = <!--board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation-->\n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| family             =\n| awards             = <!--notable national level awards only-->\n| website            = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Warwick]] (MA, PhD)\n| thesis_title       = \n| thesis_url         = \n| thesis_year        = \n| school_tradition   = \n| doctoral_advisor   = \n| influences         = \n| era                = \n| discipline         = [[Sociology]]\n| sub_discipline     = <!--academic discipline specialist area \u2013 e.g. Sub-atomic research, 20th Century Danish specialist, Pauline research, Arcadian and Ugaritic specialist-->\n| workplaces         = [[StopSO (Specialist Treatment Organisation for the Prevention of Sexual Offending)]]\n| doctoral_students  = \n| notable_students   = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| main_interests     = \n| notable_works      = \n| notable_ideas      = \n| influenced         = <!--must be referenced from a third party source-->\n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\nDr. '''Sarah D. Goode''' is a British [[sociologist]], writer, [[CEO]] of StopSO, and former Honorary Researcher and Coordinator of the Center for Research and Policy for the Study of Community Welfare at the [[University of Winchester]], UK.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/author/dr-sarah-d-goode/ | title = Dr Sarah D Goode | access-date = 13 October 2017 | website= Huffpost}}</ref> She is the author of books including \"Understanding and addressing adult sexual attraction to children\" and \"Paedophiles in Society\", in which she analyses the situation of [[paedophilia]] in contemporary Western society.<ref>{{cite book |last=Goode |first=Sarah |year=2010 |access-date=13 October 2017 |title=Understanding and Addressing Adult Sexual Attraction to Children |url=https://books.google.com/?id=pKcQY5fUfFAC |location= London|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-203-87374-8 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://us.macmillan.com/author/sarahdgoode |title=Sarah D. Goode Palgrave-MacMillan |accessdate=2017-10-13 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130924030553/http://us.macmillan.com/author/sarahdgoode |archivedate=24 September 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Education and work==\nShe trained as a paediatric occupational therapist, going on to study an MA in Sociological Research in Healthcare at the University of Warwick before studying for a PhD in Sociology.<ref name=psychotherapyUK>{{cite web | url = https://www.psychotherapyuk.co.uk/dr-sarah-goode/ | title = Dr Sarah Goode | access-date = 13 October 2017 | website= psychotherapyUK}}</ref>\n\nShe worked as a lecturer at the Warwick Medical School and was a senior lecturer at the University of Winchester, leading the Research and Policy Centre for the Study of Wellbeing in Communities.<ref name=psychotherapyUK/>\n\nHer work was featured in a [[Channel Four]] documentary, and she has appeared in interviews on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] and the [[BBC]].<ref name=psychotherapyUK/><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/i-am-a-paedophile-is-our-approach-to-sex-offenders-helping-to-create-more-victims-9880699.html | title = 'I am a paedophile': Is our approach to sex offenders helping to create more victims? |author=Steve Humphries |date=24 November 2014|access-date = 11 April 2020 | website= The Independent}}</ref>\n\nShe has praised the work of the [[Prevention Project Dunkelfeld]] and the [[Lucy Faithfull, Baroness Faithfull|Lucy Faithfull Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/dr-sarah-d-goode/chemical-castration-paedophiles_b_9658586.html | title = Chemical Castration - or Compassion for Paedophiles? |author=Sarah Goode |date=12 April 2016|access-date = 11 April 2020 | website= Huffpost}}</ref> Whilst being critical of practices such as [[chemical castration]] and critical of current clinical [[psychiatric]] criteria, believing them to be too narrow.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Rickard |first1=Diana |date=September 2013 |title=Reviewed Work: Paedophiles in Society: Reflecting on Sexuality, Abuse and Hope by Sarah D. Goode |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/23524433?seq=1 |journal=Contemporary Sociology |volume=42 |issue=5 |pages=745-747 |doi= |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Understanding and addressing adult sexual attraction to children===\nIn her book ''Understanding and addressing adult sexual attraction to children'', presents case studies based on interviews she conducted with [[pedophiles]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Smith|first1=Clarissa|date=November 2010 |title=Review: Sarah D. Goode, Understanding and Addressing Sexual Attraction to Children: A Study of Paedophiles in Contemporary Society |url=https://www.participations.org/Volume%207/Issue%202/PDF/smith.pdf |journal=Participation: Journal of Audience and Reception Studies |volume=7 |issue=2 |pages=396-398 |doi= |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> She uses these case studies, as well as previous studies to counteract some of the false beliefs and alarmism that developed in the late 1970s in the United States, and in the early 1980s in Europe.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Plummer|first1=Ken|date=November 2010 |title=Understanding and addressing adult sexual attraction to children: a study of paedophiles in contemporary society |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/1743727X.2010.512100?journalCode=cwse20 |journal=International Journal of Research & Method in Education |volume=33 |issue=3 |pages=318-319 |doi=10.1080/1743727X.2010.512100 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* {{citation|author=Sarah D. Goode|title= Understanding and addressing adult sexual attraction to children: a study of paedophiles in contemporary society| publisher=Routledge|place=London/New York|year=2010|ISBN= 9780415446266 |lang=en|ref=none}}\n* {{citation|author=Sarah D. Goode|title= Paedophiles in society: reflecting on sexuality, abuse and hope| publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|place=Basingstoke|year=2011|ISBN= 9780230271883|lang=en|ref=none}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goode, Sarah D}}\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Warwick]]\n[[Category:British sociologists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women sociologists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{UK-sociologist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "<noinclude><!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Sarah D. Goode|timestamp=20200410170421|year=2020|month=April|day=10|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Sarah D. Goode|date=10 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point --></noinclude>\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix   = Dr\n| name               = Sarah D. Goode\n| honorific_suffix   = PhD\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         = <!-- use only if different from full/othernames -->\n| birth_date         = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}}  -->\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| region             = \n| nationality        = British\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = CEO, writer\n| period             = \n| known_for          = {{Plainlist|\n* ''[[Understanding and Addressing Adult Sexual Attraction to Children]]''\n* ''Paedophiles in Society''}}\n| title              = \n| boards             = <!--board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation-->\n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| family             =\n| awards             = <!--notable national level awards only-->\n| website            = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Warwick]] (MA, PhD)\n| thesis_title       = \n| thesis_url         = \n| thesis_year        = \n| school_tradition   = \n| doctoral_advisor   = \n| influences         = \n| era                = \n| discipline         = [[Sociology]]\n| sub_discipline     = <!--academic discipline specialist area \u2013 e.g. Sub-atomic research, 20th Century Danish specialist, Pauline research, Arcadian and Ugaritic specialist-->\n| workplaces         = [[StopSO (Specialist Treatment Organisation for the Prevention of Sexual Offending)]]\n| doctoral_students  = \n| notable_students   = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| main_interests     = \n| notable_works      = \n| notable_ideas      = \n| influenced         = <!--must be referenced from a third party source-->\n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\nDr. '''Sarah D. Goode''' is a British [[sociologist]], writer, [[CEO]] of StopSO, and former Honorary Researcher and Coordinator of the Center for Research and Policy for the Study of Community Welfare at the [[University of Winchester]], UK.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/author/dr-sarah-d-goode/ | title = Dr Sarah D Goode | access-date = 13 October 2017 | website= Huffpost}}</ref> She is the author of books including \"Understanding and addressing adult sexual attraction to children\" and \"Paedophiles in Society\", in which she analyses the situation of [[paedophilia]] in contemporary Western society.<ref>{{cite book |last=Goode |first=Sarah |year=2010 |access-date=13 October 2017 |title=Understanding and Addressing Adult Sexual Attraction to Children |url=https://books.google.com/?id=pKcQY5fUfFAC |location= London|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-203-87374-8 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://us.macmillan.com/author/sarahdgoode |title=Sarah D. Goode Palgrave-MacMillan |accessdate=2017-10-13 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130924030553/http://us.macmillan.com/author/sarahdgoode |archivedate=24 September 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Education and work==\nShe trained as a paediatric occupational therapist, going on to study an MA in Sociological Research in Healthcare at the University of Warwick before studying for a PhD in Sociology.<ref name=psychotherapyUK>{{cite web | url = https://www.psychotherapyuk.co.uk/dr-sarah-goode/ | title = Dr Sarah Goode | access-date = 13 October 2017 | website= psychotherapyUK}}</ref>\n\nShe worked as a lecturer at the Warwick Medical School and was a senior lecturer at the University of Winchester, leading the Research and Policy Centre for the Study of Wellbeing in Communities.<ref name=psychotherapyUK/>\n\nHer work was featured in a [[Channel Four]] documentary, and she has appeared in interviews on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] and the [[BBC]].<ref name=psychotherapyUK/><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/i-am-a-paedophile-is-our-approach-to-sex-offenders-helping-to-create-more-victims-9880699.html | title = 'I am a paedophile': Is our approach to sex offenders helping to create more victims? |author=Steve Humphries |date=24 November 2014|access-date = 11 April 2020 | website= The Independent}}</ref>\n\nShe has praised the work of the [[Prevention Project Dunkelfeld]] and the [[Lucy Faithfull, Baroness Faithfull|Lucy Faithfull Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/dr-sarah-d-goode/chemical-castration-paedophiles_b_9658586.html | title = Chemical Castration - or Compassion for Paedophiles? |author=Sarah Goode |date=12 April 2016|access-date = 11 April 2020 | website= Huffpost}}</ref> Whilst being critical of practices such as [[chemical castration]] and critical of current clinical [[psychiatric]] criteria, believing them to be too narrow.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Rickard |first1=Diana |date=September 2013 |title=Reviewed Work: Paedophiles in Society: Reflecting on Sexuality, Abuse and Hope by Sarah D. Goode |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/23524433?seq=1 |journal=Contemporary Sociology |volume=42 |issue=5 |pages=745-747 |doi= |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Understanding and addressing adult sexual attraction to children===\nIn her book ''Understanding and addressing adult sexual attraction to children'', presents case studies based on interviews she conducted with [[pedophiles]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Smith|first1=Clarissa|date=November 2010 |title=Review: Sarah D. Goode, Understanding and Addressing Sexual Attraction to Children: A Study of Paedophiles in Contemporary Society |url=https://www.participations.org/Volume%207/Issue%202/PDF/smith.pdf |journal=Participation: Journal of Audience and Reception Studies |volume=7 |issue=2 |pages=396-398 |doi= |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> She uses these case studies, as well as previous studies to counteract some of the false beliefs and alarmism that developed in the late 1970s in the United States, and in the early 1980s in Europe.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Plummer|first1=Ken|date=November 2010 |title=Understanding and addressing adult sexual attraction to children: a study of paedophiles in contemporary society |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/1743727X.2010.512100?journalCode=cwse20 |journal=International Journal of Research & Method in Education |volume=33 |issue=3 |pages=318-319 |doi=doi.org/10.1080/1743727X.2010.512100 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* {{citation|author=Sarah D. Goode|title= Understanding and addressing adult sexual attraction to children: a study of paedophiles in contemporary society| publisher=Routledge|place=London/New York|year=2010|ISBN= 9780415446266 |lang=en|ref=none}}\n* {{citation|author=Sarah D. Goode|title= Paedophiles in society: reflecting on sexuality, abuse and hope| publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|place=Basingstoke|year=2011|ISBN= 9780230271883|lang=en|ref=none}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goode, Sarah D}}\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Warwick]]\n[[Category:British sociologists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women sociologists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{UK-sociologist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUnderstanding and addressing adult sexual attraction to children:Fixed doi error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sarah_D._Goode"}
{"title_page": "Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on long-term care facilities", "text_new": "{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] has impacted long-term care facilities and senior's residences''' around the world.\n\n==Canada==\n\nIn British Columbia, the number of cases in long-term care facilities jumped from 9 to 235, including 143 residents and 92 staff.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Little |first1=Simon |title=B.C.\u2019s coronavirus death toll hits 50 as cases mount in long-term care homes |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6800965/bc-coronavirus-update-april-9/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Global News |publisher=Corus |date=9 April 2020 |location=Vancouver BC}}</ref>\n\nIn Ontario on March 18, an outbreak began in the Pinecrest Nursing Home in [[Bobcaygeon]], and as of April 6, 26 residents have died as a result of COVID-19\u2014more than one third of the nursing home's total residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cp24.com/two-more-covid-19-deaths-at-bobcayeon-ont-seniors-residence-1.4882611|title=Two more COVID-19 deaths at Bobcayeon, Ont. seniors' residence|publisher=cp24.com|date=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cp24.com/three-more-people-with-covid-19-have-died-at-bobcaygeon-long-term-care-home-death-toll-now-at-26-1.4884390|title=Three more people with COVID-19 have died at Bobcaygeon long-term care home, death toll now at 26|publisher=cp24.com|date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> On April 6, the City of Toronto discovered that a large shipment of Chinese-made masks delivered to its long-term care facilities were defective.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Staff staff |title=City of Toronto recalls defective masks to long-term care homes; Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs Canada tests positive for COVID-19; Alberta releases projections |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2020/04/07/uk-pm-boris-johnson-spent-the-night-at-the-icu-3m-will-continue-to-send-masks-to-canada-japan-declares-state-of-emergency.html |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Toronto Star |date=7 April 2020 |location=Toronto ON}}</ref>\n\nIn Quebec, a team of health care professionals inspecting [[R\u00e9sidence Herron]] after a resident's death from COVID-19 found the facility largely abandoned by staff. Living conditions inside were similar to \"a concentration camp\", according to the officials.<ref name=\"2020-04-10-MG-find-bodies\">{{cite news |last1=Derfel |first1=Aaron |title=Public health, police find bodies, feces at Dorval seniors\u2019 residence: sources |url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/public-health-police-find-bodies-feces-at-dorval-seniors-residence-sources/wcm/19011f52-7b04-41c4-a674-93bc26283749/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Montreal Gazette |date=10 April 2020 |location=Montreal QC}}</ref>\n\n==United Kingdom==\n\n[[Sky News]] correspondent [[Alex Crawford]] wrote an editorial about care homes in general, and in relation to COVID, suggesting the situation was a \"scandal\" that future generations would question. She also noted care assistants' working conditions, including [[zero hour contracts]], and homes urging sick employees to come in anyway.<ref name=\"2020-04-11-SN\">{{cite news |last1=Crawford |first1=Alex |title=Coronavirus: What's happening in UK care homes right now is a scandal our grandchildren will ask about |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-why-care-homes-are-the-scandal-among-scandals-during-this-pandemic-11971795 |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Sky News |date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nTo prevent bringing COVID-19 into the facility, assistants at Liverpool's Beechside Home have moved in, as of April 2020.<ref name=\"2020-04-11-SN\" /> Nearby Oak Spring has had 14 deaths in two weeks, as of mid-April; only two of the deceased were tested, and both were positive for COVID-19.<ref name=\"2020-04-11-SN\" /> As of early April, that facility was operating with a quarter of its normal staffing, after the staff or their families were exhibiting symptoms, and were self isolating. Two-thirds of remaining residents were exhibiting symptoms.<ref>{{cite news |title=Liverpool care home secures extra staff after residents show Covid-19 symptoms |url=https://www.itv.com/news/granada/2020-04-01/liverpool-care-home-secures-extra-staff-after-residents-show-covid-19-symptoms/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=ITV |date=1 April 2020 |location=Liverpool UK}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: 'Amazing response' to struggling care home's staffing plea |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-merseyside-52118871 |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=1 April 2020 |location=Liverpool UK}}</ref>\n\n==United States==\n\nAs of April 11, 2020, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that there were nearly 2000 nursing home resident deaths in the New York, New Jersey, and Connecticut region. There were 4630 positive cases in New York's 613 licensed facilities, as of April 10.<ref name=\"2020-04-11-NYT\">{{cite news |author1=Amy Julia Harris |author2=John Leland |author3=Tracey Tully |title=Nearly 2,000 Dead as Coronavirus Ravages Nursing Homes in N.Y. Region |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/11/nyregion/nursing-homes-deaths-coronavirus.html |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=11 April 2020 |location=New York City NY}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{COVID-19 |state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|long-term care]]\n[[Category:Elderly care]]\n\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] has impacted long-term care facilities and senior's residences''' around the world.\n\n==Canada==\n\nIn British Columbia, the number of cases in long-term care facilities jumped from 9 to 235, including 143 residents and 92 staff.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Little |first1=Simon |title=B.C.\u2019s coronavirus death toll hits 50 as cases mount in long-term care homes |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6800965/bc-coronavirus-update-april-9/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Global News |publisher=Corus |date=9 April 2020 |location=Vancouver BC}}</ref>\n\nIn Ontario on March 18, an outbreak began in the Pinecrest Nursing Home in [[Bobcaygeon]], and as of April 6, 26 residents have died as a result of COVID-19\u2014more than one third of the nursing home's total residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cp24.com/two-more-covid-19-deaths-at-bobcayeon-ont-seniors-residence-1.4882611|title=Two more COVID-19 deaths at Bobcayeon, Ont. seniors' residence|publisher=cp24.com|date=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cp24.com/three-more-people-with-covid-19-have-died-at-bobcaygeon-long-term-care-home-death-toll-now-at-26-1.4884390|title=Three more people with COVID-19 have died at Bobcaygeon long-term care home, death toll now at 26|publisher=cp24.com|date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> On April 6, the City of Toronto discovered that a large shipment of Chinese-made masks delivered to its long-term care facilities were defective.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Staff staff |title=City of Toronto recalls defective masks to long-term care homes; Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs Canada tests positive for COVID-19; Alberta releases projections |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2020/04/07/uk-pm-boris-johnson-spent-the-night-at-the-icu-3m-will-continue-to-send-masks-to-canada-japan-declares-state-of-emergency.html |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Toronto Star |date=7 April 2020 |location=Toronto ON}}</ref>\n\nIn Quebec, a team of health care professionals inspecting [[R\u00e9sidence Herron]] after a resident's death from COVID-19 found the facility largely abandoned by staff. Living conditions inside were similar to \"a concentration camp\", according to the officials.<ref name=\"2020-04-10-MG-find-bodies\">{{cite news |last1=Derfel |first1=Aaron |title=Public health, police find bodies, feces at Dorval seniors\u2019 residence: sources |url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/public-health-police-find-bodies-feces-at-dorval-seniors-residence-sources/wcm/19011f52-7b04-41c4-a674-93bc26283749/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Montreal Gazette |date=10 April 2020 |location=Montreal QC}}</ref>\n\n==United Kingdom==\n\n[[Sky News]] correspondent [[Alex Crawford]] wrote an editorial about care homes in general, and in relation to COVID, suggesting the situation was a \"scandal\" that future generations would question. She also noted care assistants' working conditions, including [[zero hour contracts]], and homes urging sick employees to come in anyway.<ref name=\"2020-04-11-SN\">{{cite news |last1=Crawford |first1=Alex |title=Coronavirus: What's happening in UK care homes right now is a scandal our grandchildren will ask about |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-why-care-homes-are-the-scandal-among-scandals-during-this-pandemic-11971795 |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Sky News |date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nTo prevent bringing COVID-19 into the facility, assistants at Liverpool's Beechside Home have moved in, as of April 2020.<ref name=\"2020-04-11-SN\" /> Nearby Oak Spring has had 14 deaths in two weeks, as of mid-April; only two of the deceased were tested, and both were positive for COVID-19.<ref name=\"2020-04-11-SN\" /> As of early April, that facility was operating with a quarter of its normal staffing, and two-thirds of remaining residents were exhibiting symptoms.<ref>{{cite news |title=Liverpool care home secures extra staff after residents show Covid-19 symptoms |url=https://www.itv.com/news/granada/2020-04-01/liverpool-care-home-secures-extra-staff-after-residents-show-covid-19-symptoms/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=ITV |date=1 April 2020 |location=Liverpool UK}}</ref>\n\n==United States==\n\nAs of April 11, 2020, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that there were nearly 2000 nursing home resident deaths in the New York, New Jersey, and Connecticut region. There were 4630 positive cases in New York's 613 licensed facilities, as of April 10.<ref name=\"2020-04-11-NYT\">{{cite news |author1=Amy Julia Harris |author2=John Leland |author3=Tracey Tully |title=Nearly 2,000 Dead as Coronavirus Ravages Nursing Homes in N.Y. Region |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/11/nyregion/nursing-homes-deaths-coronavirus.html |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=11 April 2020 |location=New York City NY}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{COVID-19 |state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|long-term care]]\n[[Category:Elderly care]]\n\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zanimum", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUnited Kingdom", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impact_of_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic_on_long-term_care_facilities"}
{"title_page": "Cycling at the 2000 Summer Olympics", "text_new": "{{short description|Cycling at the Olympics}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox Olympic event\n| event       = Cycling\n| games       = 2000 Summer\n| image       = Dunc Gray Veledrom in Bass Hill New South Wales.jpg\n| image_size  = 300px\n| caption     = The Dunc Gray Velodrome\n| venues      = [[Western Sydney Parklands]]<br>[[Sydney]] and surrounding area<br>[[Dunc Gray Velodrome]]\n| date        = 16 September&nbsp;- 20 September\n| competitors = 462\n| nations     = 55\n| prev        = [[cycling at the 1996 Summer Olympics|1996]]\n| next        = [[cycling at the 2004 Summer Olympics|2004]]\n}}\n'''At the [[2000 Summer Olympics]]''', 3 different [[bicycle racing]] disciplines were contested: [[Road bicycle racing|Road cycling]], [[track cycling]], and [[mountain biking]].<ref name=\"SR\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/2000/CYC/ |title=Cycling at the 2000 Sydney Summer Games |work=Sports Reference |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Road cycling==\n{| {{MedalistTable|type=Event}}\n|-\n| Men's road race<br>{{DetailsLink|Cycling at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's individual road race}}\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Jan Ullrich]]|GER|2000 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Alexander Vinokourov]]|KAZ|2000 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Andreas Kl\u00f6den]]|GER|2000 Summer}}\n|-\n| Men's time trial<br>{{DetailsLink|Cycling at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's road time trial}}\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Viatcheslav Ekimov]]|RUS|2000 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Jan Ullrich]]|GER|2000 Summer}}\n|Vacated\n|-\n| Women's road race<br>{{DetailsLink|Cycling at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's individual road race}}\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Leontien Zijlaard]]|NED|2000 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Hanka Kupfernagel]]|GER|2000 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCmedalist|[[Diana \u017dili\u016bt\u0117]]|LTU|2000 Summer}}\n|-\n| Women's time trial<br>{{DetailsLink|Cycling at