Burt]]'' (2011) An album of Bacharach songs, arranged and co-produced by Bacharach.\n\n;As musician\n* For [[Neil Diamond]]:\n* ''[[Heartlight (album)|Heartlight]]'', 1982; ''[[Primitive (Neil Diamond album)|Primitive]]'', 1984; ''[[Headed for the Future]]'', 1986.\n* For [[Aretha Franklin]]:\n* ''[[What You See Is What You Sweat]]'', 1991.\n* For [[Dionne Warwick]]:\n* ''[[Reservations for Two]]'', 1987; ''[[Friends Can Be Lovers]]'', 1993.\n* For [[Barbra Streisand]]:\n* ''[[Till I Loved You (album)|Till I Loved You]]'', 1988.\n* For [[Natalie Cole]]:\n* ''[[Everlasting (Natalie Cole album)|Everlasting]]'', 1987.\n* For [[Carly Simon]]:\n* ''[[Christmas Is Almost Here]]'', 2002.\n* With [[Roberta Flack]]:\n* ''[[I'm the One (Roberta Flack album)|I'm the One]]'', 1982.\n* With [[Ray Parker Jr.]]:\n* ''[[After Dark (Ray Parker Jr. album)|After Dark]]'', 1987.\n\n;Tribute albums\n* [[Stan Getz]] released the album ''[[What the World Needs Now: Stan Getz Plays Burt Bacharach and Hal David]]'' in 1968.\n* Jazz musician [[John Zorn]] produced a 2-CD set of Bacharach tunes (1997), featuring several avant-garde musicians, as part of his ''Great Jewish Music'' series.\n* Marie McAuliffe's Ark Sextet released the Bacharach tribute album \"Refractions\" in 1998. McAuliffe had been featured on John Zorn's tribute album.\n* ''[[To Hal and Bacharach]]'' is a 1998 tribute album with 18 tunes, performed by notable Australian artists.\n* ''That's New Pussycat!: Surf Tribute to Burt Bacharach'' (2001)\n* [[Michael Ball (singer)|Michael Ball]] recorded the album ''Back to Bacharach'' in 2007\n* ''What the World Needs Now: Big Deal Recording Artists Perform the Songs of Burt Bacharach''\n* ''All Kinds of People: Love Burt Bacharach'' (2010) is a tribute album produced by [[Jim O'Rourke (musician)|Jim O'Rourke]], featuring covers from [[Haruomi Hosono]] and [[Thurston Moore]] among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Jim-ORourke-All-Kinds-Of-People-Love-Burt-Bacharach/master/803741|title=Jim O'Rourke - All Kinds Of People: Love Burt Bacharach|publisher=Discogs}}</ref>\n* ''This Girl's In Love (A Bacharach & David Songbook)'', released in November 2016 by Anglo-Pakistani singer-songwriter [[Rumer (musician)|Rumer]] (real name Sarah Joyce).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin|normalfont=yes}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Farina|first=William|authorlink=William Farina|title=The German Cabaret Legacy in American Popular Music|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YdUiL1XHZKkC|year=2013|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-6863-8}}\n* {{cite book |first=Andrew Grant|last=Jackson |title=1965: The Most Revolutionary Year in Music |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-QI3BAAAQBAJ|date=2015 |publisher=Thomas Dunne Books |isbn=978-1-250-05962-8 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links | d=Q212762 | c=Category:Burt_Bacharach | n=no | v=no | voy=no | b=no | wikt=no | species=no | m=no | mw=no | s=no}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0000820|name=Burt Bacharach}}\n* {{Shof|id=40|name=Burt Bacharach}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071228075536/http://wse65068.ta22.talkactive.net/hitmaker/ A database of recordings of Burt Bacharach's songs]\n\n{{Burt Bacharach}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Burt Bacharach\n| list =\n{{Academy Award Best Original Score}}\n{{Academy Award Best Original Song}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Original Music}}\n{{DramaDesk Music}}\n{{Golden Globe Award for Best Original Score}}\n{{Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song}}\n{{Grammy Award for Song of the Year}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best Score Soundtrack for Visual Media}}\n{{Gershwin Prize}}\n{{Polar Music Prize}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bacharach, Burt}}\n[[Category:Burt Bacharach| ]]\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Kansas City, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Writers from Kansas City, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Jewish American composers]]\n[[Category: